## Summary
The dev server crashed with `SUPABASE_URL is not defined`, so the site never rendered on localhost. Root cause was the Supabase config being referenced as a bare global plus missing module exports/imports. This makes the landing route (`home` → `AuthPage`) render again **and look correct**, working in **demo (mock) mode** out of the box when no `.env` is present.

What changed:
- `app/data/mockdata.jsx`: the file used `SUPABASE_URL` as an undeclared global (the actual `ReferenceError`). Now imports it, and `export`s `isMockMode` / `MOCK_STATE` (they were declared but never exported, even though `Authpage` imports them).
  ```diff
  +import { SUPABASE_URL } from "../pages/config";
  -const isMockMode = SUPABASE_URL.includes("YOUR_PROJECT");
  +export const isMockMode = !SUPABASE_URL || SUPABASE_URL.includes("YOUR_PROJECT");
  -const MOCK_STATE = { ... }
  +export const MOCK_STATE = { ... }
  ```
- `app/pages/config.jsx`: read env via Vite (`import.meta.env.VITE_*`) with placeholder fallbacks so the app degrades to mock mode instead of crashing when env vars are absent.
- `app/pages/lecturer/Authpage.jsx` and `app/pages/student/logentries.jsx`: fixed import paths/casing that didn't match committed files (`mockData`→`mockdata`, `components/ui/Alert`→`components/alert`). These fail on case-sensitive filesystems / Docker builds even though they resolve on Windows.
- `app/root.tsx`: import `./styles/index.css`. The 293-line stylesheet with all the real design (`.auth-wrap`, `.btn-primary`, etc.) was never loaded — only `app.css` (Tailwind base) was — so the page rendered unstyled.
  ```diff
   import "./app.css";
  +import "./styles/index.css";
  ```

To use a real Supabase project, add a `.env` (already gitignored) with `VITE_SUPABASE_URL` and `VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`.

## Note (out of scope, not fixed here)
Other non-routed files have the same class of problems (e.g. `utils/helper.jsx` has no exports though `sidebar.jsx`/`logentries.jsx` import `{ initials }`

Browser-native focus scroll adjustment fires after the existing double-rAF restore pass, silently overwriting captured positions. Additionally, `selected → selected` transitions had no capture/restore path at all.

## Root cause — two independent failure paths

| Transition | Pre-fix behaviour | Cause |
|---|---|---|
| `normal → selected` | Incident jumps `959 → 405` | Browser deferred focus-scroll overwrites both rAF restore passes |
| `selected → selected` | Crew jumps `959 → 783` | Guard `isSelectedLayout == willBeSelectedLayout` returned early — no restore issued |
| `selected → normal` | Stable | Existing path, unaffected |

## Changes

### `portfolioPlanBoardScrollSync.js` — outlast browser focus-scroll deferral

Adds a `setTimeout(0)` pass after the double-rAF, scheduling a macrotask that runs after the browser completes layout/paint (including any deferred focus adjustment) and re-asserts the snapshot one final time.

```js
window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
    applySnapshot();
    window.requestAnimationFrame(function () {
        applySnapshot();
        // Macrotask boundary: outlasts native focus-scroll adjustment.
        window.setTimeout(function () {
            applySnapshot();
            resolve();
        }, 0);
    });
});
```

### `PortfolioPlanBoardPage.razor` — enable restore for `selected → selected`

Changes the early-return guard so only `normal → normal` transitions skip capture/restore:

```csharp
// Before
if (isSelectedLayout == willBeSelectedLayout) return;

// After — skip only when no panel is involved on either side
if (!isSelectedLayout && !willBeSelectedLayout) return;
```

This ensures all three panel-involved transitions (`normal → selected`, `selected → selected`, `selected → normal`) go through capture/restore.

## Validation

Mock runtime, profile 1 — all transitions stable:

| Transition | Axis | Incident | Crew |
|---|---:|---:|---:|
| Baseline | 650 | 639 | 639 |
| normal → selected | 650 | 639 | 639 |
| selected

The desktop **Snip** button was wired but produced no observable effect when clicked in real usage. This change hardens protocol launch behavior and removes button semantics that could interfere with click handling.

- **Launch path reliability**
  - Switches primary invocation to direct protocol navigation (`window.location.assign('ms-screenclip:')`).
  - Keeps a DOM-anchor fallback launch path if the primary call throws.
  - Centralizes protocol/message constants and fallback helper to reduce drift across paths.

- **Toolbar button semantics**
  - Sets the Snip control to `type="button"` so it is never affected by default button/form behavior.

- **User + diagnostic feedback**
  - Uses a single, consistent launch toast message across primary/fallback paths.
  - Improves error logging context when both launch attempts fail.

```js
const snipProtocol = 'ms-screenclip:';

try {
  window.location.assign(snipProtocol);
  Toast.show(launchMsg);
} catch (err) {
  launchViaAnchor();
}
```

Adds an optional `difficulty` field (Beginner / Intermediate / Advanced) to activities, plus a sidebar filter so students can find level-appropriate activities. Activities without a difficulty are treated as open to all levels and surface under every filter selection.

## Changes

- **`database.py`** — Added `difficulty` to seed activities (Beginner: Chess Club, Soccer Team; Intermediate: Programming Class, Basketball Team, Debate Team; Advanced: Math Club, Robotics, Science Olympiad, Sunday Chess Tournament; unset: Morning Fitness, Art Club, Manga Maniacs, Drama Club)

- **`index.html`** — New "Filter by difficulty" section in the sidebar with All / Beginner / Intermediate / Advanced buttons

- **`app.js`** — Added `currentDifficulty` state and filter logic in `displayFilteredActivities()`:
  ```js
  if (currentDifficulty !== "") {
    const activityDifficulty = details.difficulty;
    // Activities with no difficulty are for all levels — always include them
    if (activityDifficulty && activityDifficulty !== currentDifficulty) {
      return;
    }
  }
  ```
  Difficulty filter is client-side only (no new API param needed). Event listeners follow the existing pattern for category/day/time filters.

- **`styles.css`** — Extended existing filter button selectors to cover `.difficulty-filter` / `.difficulty-filters`; no new styles needed.

Difficulty is intentionally not rendered on the activity card.

Students requested a dark mode option. Adds a toggle button in the top-right header that switches between dark and light themes, with the preference persisted via `localStorage`.

## Changes

- **`styles.css`** — Added `[data-theme="dark"]` CSS block overriding all color variables for dark mode; added `#dark-mode-toggle` button styles; set `#user-controls` to flex layout
- **`index.html`** — Added `#dark-mode-toggle` button in the header's `#user-controls` alongside the existing login controls
- **`app.js`** — Added `applyTheme()` which sets `data-theme` on `<html>`, updates button label (🌙/☀️), and persists to `localStorage`; restores saved theme on load

```js
function applyTheme(theme) {
  document.documentElement.setAttribute("data-theme", theme);
  darkModeToggle.textContent = theme === "dark" ? "☀️ Light Mode" : "🌙 Dark Mode";
  localStorage.setItem("theme", theme);
}
const savedTheme = localStorage.getItem("theme") || "light";
applyTheme(savedTheme);
```

The speech_lab QA page was receiving valid AI responses but failing to extract a transcript because the model returned free-form text rather than a parseable structure.

## Changes

**Prompt (`speech_lab.html`)**
- Replaced the vague `message` prompt with an explicit instruction requiring the model to respond in a fixed four-section format: `TRANSCRIPT:`, `LANGUAGE_FEEDBACK:`, `LOGIC_FEEDBACK:`, `NEXT_STEP:`

**Parsing (`speech_lab.html`)**
- Removed the heuristic `transcript[:\s]+` regex that only caught single-line matches
- Added `parseStructuredReply()` — a deterministic section extractor using a single `RegExp` over all four keys:

```js
function parseStructuredReply(reply) {
  const KEYS = ['TRANSCRIPT', 'LANGUAGE_FEEDBACK', 'LOGIC_FEEDBACK', 'NEXT_STEP'];
  const pattern = new RegExp(
    '(' + KEYS.join('|') + '):\\s*([\\s\\S]*?)(?=\\n(?:' + KEYS.join('|') + '):|$)',
    'g'
  );
  const sections = {};
  let m;
  while ((m = pattern.exec(reply)) !== null) sections[m[1]] = m[2].trim();
  return sections;
}
```

**Rendering**
- Transcript box ← `sections.TRANSCRIPT`; feedback box ← the three remaining sections joined
- If `TRANSCRIPT` is absent: transcript box shows `TRANSCRIPT_MISSING`, feedback box shows full raw AI response for debugging
- All existing PASS/FAIL checklist items and audio diagnostics are unchanged
